<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="idempotent-write-tools">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>ai</group>
    <domain>ai-agents</domain>
    <summary>Every write tool must accept an idempotency_key so retries replay instead of duplicating side effects. Destructive/expensive operations split into preview + apply pairs for review before commit.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>idempotency</tag>
      <tag>tooling</tag>
      <tag>agents</tag>
      <tag>reliability</tag>
      <tag>safety</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Idempotent Write Tools — Keys + Preview/Apply Pairs</title>
    <summary>Every tool that mutates state must accept an idempotency_key from the agent and be safe to re-run with the same key (returns the same result without duplicating the side effect). Destructive or expensive operations ship as *_preview + *_apply pairs, separating the agent's reasoning step from the irreversible commit step. Tools time out, networks flake, agent loops retry on transient errors — un-keyed writes silently double-charge, double-deploy, double-email. Idempotency keys turn every retry into a no-op replay; preview/apply pairs let the agent show its work before committing.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Production agent runs fail mid-tool roughly an order of magnitude more often than human-issued API calls — long horizon means many tool calls, which compounds the flake rate. Without a key, the orchestrator cannot tell the difference between "the call succeeded but the response was lost" and "the call never happened", so it retries and the side effect runs twice. Stripe, AWS, GitHub, and every payment provider built idempotency keys for exactly this reason; agent tools inherit the same constraint, amplified by the agent's eagerness to retry on ambiguous errors. Preview/apply separates the model's reasoning step from the irreversible step, giving the human (or a guard agent) a chance to veto.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Any tool that mutates external state: payments, emails, file deletes, infra changes, DB writes, external API POSTs.</item>
        <item>Tools whose side effect is destructive (delete) or expensive (deploy, send email, charge card) — split into *_preview + *_apply.</item>
        <item>When the agent runs in a loop with automatic retry on tool errors.</item>
        <item>When tools are exposed via MCP gateways with at-least-once delivery semantics.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pure reads (get_*, search_*, list_*) — no side effect, no key needed; bloating the schema confuses the model.</item>
        <item>Append-only telemetry where duplicates are tolerable (metric emits, debug logs).</item>
        <item>Tools whose underlying API is already idempotent by content hash (e.g., S3 PUT with same body) — passing a key adds noise.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="The Idempotency Key Contract">
      <p>An idempotency key is a string (typically a UUID or a deterministic hash of the operation) that the agent generates ONCE per logical write and resends on every retry. The tool stores key → result for at least 24h. Second call with same key returns the stored result without running the side effect again.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Every tool whose execute mutates external state MUST accept a required idempotency_key: str parameter. The tool MUST persist key → result for &gt;= 24h and short-circuit on key hit. Reads MUST NOT take the parameter.</statement>
        <rationale>Long agent loops retry on transient tool failures; without a key, the retry cannot be distinguished from a fresh call, and the side effect runs twice. Stripe, AWS Lambda, and Square all ship the same contract for the same reason — at-least-once delivery is the default, exactly-once is a key-store away.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Stripe refund with idempotency">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[@tool
def stripe_refund_charge(charge_id: str, amount_cents: int, idempotency_key: str) -> Refund:
    if hit := key_store.get(idempotency_key):
        return hit  # replay — no second refund
    refund = stripe.Refund.create(charge=charge_id, amount=amount_cents,
                                  idempotency_key=idempotency_key)
    key_store.set(idempotency_key, refund, ttl_seconds=86400)
    return refund]]></code>
        <note>Replay is cheap, cannot double-refund, and the key is forwarded to Stripe so even the upstream is protected.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="bad" title="Email tool without deduplication">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[@tool
def send_email(to: str, subject: str, body: str) -> dict:
    return mailer.send(to=to, subject=subject, body=body)  # no key, no dedup]]></code>
        <note>If the tool times out after the SMTP server accepted the message, the agent will retry and the user gets two emails.</note>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Generating the idempotency key INSIDE the tool (key = uuid4() at the top of execute).</description>
        <reason>The key must be the same across retries. If the tool generates it, every retry gets a fresh key and the dedup never fires.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Adding idempotency_key to read tools "for consistency".</description>
        <reason>Bloats the schema, confuses the model, costs tokens — reads are already safe to repeat.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Preview + Apply Pairs for Destructive Operations">
      <p>*_preview is a pure function: takes the operation parameters, returns the would-be result (diff, cost estimate, affected IDs) WITHOUT side effects. *_apply accepts the preview's hash plus an idempotency key and performs the action only if the hash still matches the current world state.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Operations that delete data, charge money, deploy infrastructure, or send irreversible communications MUST be exposed as a *_preview (no side effect) + *_apply (idempotent, requires preview hash) pair. The single-call form MUST NOT exist in the catalog.</statement>
        <rationale>Splits the model's plan step from the commit step. The agent — or a guard agent or human — can inspect the preview, reject obvious mistakes (deleting prod, refunding wrong customer), and only then call *_apply. The hash makes the apply phase a TOCTOU-safe commit: if the world changed between preview and apply, the apply fails fast.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Deploy with preview and apply">
        <code lang="json"><![CDATA[// Step 1 — preview, no side effect
{ "name": "deploy_preview",
  "input":  { "service": "nero-core", "ref": "main" },
  "output": { "diff": "+2 -1 services...", "estimated_cost_usd": 0.04,
              "preview_hash": "sha256:abc123" } }

// Step 2 — apply, idempotent, refers to the exact preview
{ "name": "deploy_apply",
  "input":  { "preview_hash": "sha256:abc123",
              "idempotency_key": "deploy-2026-04-25-001" },
  "output": { "deployment_id": "dep_91f2", "status": "succeeded" } }]]></code>
        <note>Agent can show the diff to the user before applying. Re-running apply with the same key is a no-op replay; if main moved, the hash mismatches and apply rejects with STALE_PREVIEW.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="bad" title="One-shot irreversible deployment">
        <code lang="json"><![CDATA[// One-shot — irreversible, no review window
{ "name": "deploy",
  "input":  { "service": "nero-core", "ref": "main" } }]]></code>
        <note>Model picks the tool, deploy runs, no chance to inspect, no idempotency. A retry on timeout double-deploys.</note>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>*_preview that internally calls the upstream "dry-run" but still mutates a cache or counter.</description>
        <reason>If preview has any observable side effect, agents cannot safely run it speculatively, and the safety property collapses.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/idempotent_tool.py" purpose="Reference Python implementation (Pydantic + key store) for a write tool with replay semantics."/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
